Sure! Here’s a simplified overview of the rules of American football:

Objective

The main goal is to score more points than the opposing team by advancing the ball into their end zone or kicking it through their goalposts.

Teams

  • Each team has 11 players on the field.
  • The game consists of four quarters, each lasting 15 minutes.

Field

  • The field is 100 yards long with two end zones (10 yards each) at either end.
  • There are yard lines every 5 yards, and a midfield line at the 50-yard mark.

Scoring

  • Touchdown (6 points): Scored by carrying the ball into the opponent's end zone or catching it there.

If you continue to gain yardage and pass the goal line at the end of the field, you get 6 points and an attempt for 1 or 2 additional points by doing a kick through the goal posts (1 point) or a pass/run across the goal again.

Then you kick the ball to the other team and they do the same as above, in the other direction.

Why are American football rules so complex?

Because Americans are big cheaters!

No, seriously, in the early days of football, teams took advantage of the rules to get an advantage.

For example, there’s a rule that prevents you from wearing anything on your uniform that’s the same colour as a football. That’s because the Carlisle Indian College used to wear football sized patches on their uniforms.

There’s a rule about the colour of the ball, because once Harvard, when playing Carlisle, brought out a crimson coloured ball.

What are the main rules for understanding American football?

It's 11 on 11.

The ball is placed on the field and the offense lines up across an imaginary line. The defense is on the other side of this "line of scrimmage."

When the offense is ready they snap the ball to the quarterback (guy who throws). From there the object of the game is to advance the ball forward by running or throwing.

Can you explain the basic rules of American football to make it enjoyable for someone new to this sport?

In order to “make it enjoyable” as you request, here’s a run down on how the game is played, rather than basic rules.

Field of Play

The field is 100 yards long by 60 yards wide with two “end zones” on either end. The field is marked in ten yards increments. The objective of the game is to advance the ball to the other team’s “end zone” thereby scoring a touchdown or field goal.
